s, music and politics, and how music is nested in and relates to broader issues in society. The essays raise important themes about knowing and understanding musical traditions and music itself as an agent of social, cultural, and political change. Music Traditions, Cultures, and Contexts will appeal to music scholars and students, as well as to a general audience interested in learning about how music functions as social process as well as sound.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aEthnomusicologie. 0aEthnomusicology. 0aMusicxHistory and criticism. 0aMusiquexHistoire et critique. 4aEthnography. 4aIndigenous Studies. 4aMusic. 7aMUSIC / Ethnomusicology.2bisacsh1 aBeckwith, John, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBowman, Rob, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCaputo, Virginia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDiamond, Beverley, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aElliott, Robin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aElliott, Robin, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aFrisbie, Charlotte J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGuilbault, Jocelyne, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKoskoff, Ellen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMoisala, Pirkko, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNettl, Bruno, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPegley, Kip, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aQureshi, Regula Burckhardt, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRosenberg, Neil V., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.g